                     <title type="complete" ref="LIT3591" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                     <incipit xml:lang="gez"></incipit>                    
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                       
                     <note>Numbered 162. 
                     </note>      
                  </msItem>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.39">
                     <locus target="#37v"/>
                     <title type="complete" ref="LIT3722" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                     <incipit xml:lang="gez"></incipit>                    
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                       
                     <note>Numbered 163. 
                     </note>      
                  </msItem>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.40">
                     <locus target="#38r"/>
                     <title type="complete" ref="LIT5008MiracleScorpionSwallowed" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                     <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወሀለወት᎓ አሐቲ᎓ ብእሲት᎓ ኃጥእት᎓ </incipit>                    
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"></explicit>                       
                     <note>Numbered 164. A sinful woman wanted to commit suicide and swallowed a scorpion. Suffering from great pain, 
                        she put on her breast an image of St. Mary. After that she gave birth to three scorpions, recovered and confessed her sins to archpriest John "according to the 
                        law of the Synodos". </note>                        
                  </msItem>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.41">
                     <locus from="38v" to="39r"/>
                     <title type="complete" ref="LIT5014MiracleSilanFood" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                     <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወሀሎ᎓ አሐዱ᎓ ብእሲ᎓ ዘስሙ᎓ ሲላን᎓ ዘሀገረ᎓ ኢቆንዮስ᎓</incipit>                    
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                       
                     <note>Numbered 165. A vision of the monk Silon in the country of ʾIqonyos: the Mother of God, appearing in the meal time, prevents harm from 
                     poor food of the monk, who feed on wild plants. </note>                        
                  </msItem>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.42">
                     <locus from="39v" to="40r"/>
                     <title type="complete" ref="LIT5015MiracleEnbabrenaFasting" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                     <incipit xml:lang="gez"> ወሀለወት᎓ አሐቲ᎓ ብእሲት᎓ በሀገረ᎓ ሮሜ᎓ በቤተ᎓ ሶፍያ᎓ ዘስማ᎓ እንባብሬና᎓ </incipit>                    
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"> In Rome, ʾƎnbābrenā lived in the house of Sophia. She had an eye disease, and fastened according to the vow she gave to the Mother 
                        of God. The faith of her husband was not big; he forced her to break the fasting. The Mother of God awarded the woman on each and filled her chest with 
                     precious jewelry. The woman understood and managed to convince her husband. The chest became enmpty again. </explicit>  
                     <note>Numbered 166. </note>                           
                  </msItem>
                  
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.43">
                        <locus from="40v" to="41v"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5017MiracleSophiaConfessor" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez"> ወሀለወት᎓ አሐቲ᎓ ብእሲት᎓ ዘስማ᎓ ሶፍያ᎓ </incipit>                    
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 167.  Sophia was from a noble Israelite lineage, and her husband was from the "lineage of Aaron". They lived on an island in the Northern Sea. 
                           The confessor Mark adviced them to deny the luxury for the sake of the poor. The wife distributed all her jewelries. The husband was angry
                           and did not permit the wife to go to the church 
                           on the feast of Presentation of Mary in the Temple, because the clothes of her wife were poor. 
                           Then she started to pray at home, and saw the heavenly liturgy in a dream. </note>                                         
                  </msItem>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.44">
                     <locus from="42r" to="43v"/>
                     <title type="complete" ref="LIT5016MiracleAboliJew" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                     <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወነበረ᎓ ውስተ᎓ ቍስጥንጥንያ᎓ ዘስሙ᎓ አቦሊ᎓ </incipit>                    
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"></explicit>                   
                     <note> Numbered 168. A story about the tradesman ʾAboli of Constantinople. He got poor and  borrowed money from the Jew Gardān on the date of 
                        St. Mary's nativity, having left his son as gage, and went for trade to the shores of the "northern Ṭegros". On the way back, having reached ʾAkko, he realised that
                        he will not be in time for repaying the debt. A delay would cause the enslavement of his son. Having prayed to the Mother of God, 
                        ʾAboli threw a box with money and a brief to the Jew
                        into the sea. The Jew received the money but nevertherless he sued ʾAboli.
                        The voice of the Mother of God, who was appealed to be a witness, compelled him to get baptized.  
                     </note>
                  </msItem> 
                     
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.45">
                        <locus target="44r"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT3652Miracle" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez"></incipit>                    
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 169. </note>                                         
                     </msItem>
                     
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.46">
                        <locus target="44v"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5018MiracleSergisAbresqilaSon" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez"> ወነበረ᎓ አሐዱ᎓ ብእሲ᎓ ክቡር᎓ ወቡሩክ᎓ ዘይፈርሆ᎓ ለእግዚአብሔር᎓ ዘስሙ᎓ ሰርጊስ᎓ </incipit>                    
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 170.  The wife and the husband broke the vow of virginity and gave birth to a son. Because of the mother's unwary words, 
                        the boy was doomed to Satan. He went to Rome where Pope Epiphanius gave him a letter to Bishop Niqonyos of Jerusalem. The latter sent the boy
                        to the monastery of Dabra Qwānṣǝl, to the ascetic Gabra Krǝstos. He entrusted the boy to the Mother of God, who saved him from Hell when Gabra 
                        Krǝstos he was celebrating the Mass for him. </note>                                         
                     </msItem>
                     
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.47">
                     <locus from="46r" to="47r"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5021MiraclePhilippNiqonya" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                     <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወነበረ᎓ ብእሲ᎓ ባዕል᎓ ወነጋዲ᎓ ዘስሙ᎓ ፊልጶስ᎓ </incipit>                    
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                   
                     <note> Numbered 171. A rich trader Philipp lived in the city of Niqonyā; he distributed all his possession among the poor. Another trader, 
                        Silān, lent him 1,000 golden coins, but Philipp used them for caritative purposes. Silān got angry about this but repented 
                        when he saw the Last Judgement at which the Mother of 
                     God is trying to save him, referring to the money given for good things. </note>                                         
                  </msItem>
                     
                    <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.48">
                     <locus from="47v" to="48r"/>
                       <title type="complete" ref="LIT5022MiraclePeterSirloyos" xml:lang="gez"/>
                     <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                       <incipit xml:lang="gez"> ወሀለዉ᎓ ክልኤቱ᎓ አኃው᎓ በሀገረ᎓ ሮሜ᎓ </incipit>                         
                     <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                   
                     <note> Numbered 173. Two brothers lived in Rome, archdeacon Peter, and Stephan, the governor of 
                        the city of ʾƎnṣǝnā. Both were greedy; Stephan robbed the church of St. Sirloryos but celebrated the commemoration of St. Peter the Apostle, 
                        and fed the poor on that day.  After he died, St. Peter reconciled him with Sirloryos and presented him to the Morther of God, who 
                        menaged to get for him a three day resurrection for recompensing the living people whom he offended. Thanks to the prayers of Stephan and Pope Fināḥas, Peter 
                     obtain the same chance. </note>                                         
                  </msItem>
                     
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.49">
                        <locus from="48r" to="49v"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5023MiracleMalkosMaryMichael" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወሀሎ᎓ አሐዱ᎓ ፈረሳዊ᎓ ዘስሙ᎓ ማልኮስ᎓ በሀገረ᎓ ንሒስ᎓ </incipit>                    
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"> </explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 170. The knight Mālkos of the city of Nǝḥis, being a sinner, celebrated the feasts of St. Mary and Archangel Michael monthly. Later he repented, intended to 
                        found a monastery, but died. Archangel Michael and St. Mary saved his soul from demons and returned it into his body. He lived 88 years after that. </note>                                         
                     </msItem>
                     
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.50">
                        <locus from="50r" to="50v"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5022MiraclePeterSirloyos" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez"> ወነበረ᎓ በሀገረ᎓ ሮሜ᎓ ሊቀ᎓ ጳጳሳት᎓ ዲበ᎓ መንበረ᎓ ጴጥሮስ᎓ ዘስሙ᎓ ጰኵሚስ᎓ </incipit>                         
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"></explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 171. CREATE AN ID!!!!!!.  Pope Pachomius stole myrrh from his own church and sold it. Apostle Peter threathened him with Gehenna. Pachomius 
                        gathered the priests, and one old man said to him that the only way of salvation is to pray to the Mother of God. First the prayers of Peter were rejected, his sin 
                        was pardoned only after the third prayer thanks to the mediation of St. Mary. With the money received for myrrh, Pachomius bought a precious stone and decorated 
                        an image of the Mother of Got with it. </note>                                         
                     </msItem>                  
                  
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.51">
                        <locus from="51r" to="52r"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5022MiraclePeterSirloyos" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወሀሎ᎓ አሐዱ᎓ ቀሲስ᎓ ውስተ᎓ አሐቲ᎓ ሀገር᎓ እምብሔረ᎓ ግብጽ᎓  </incipit>                    
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"></explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 172.  CREATE AN ID!!!!!!. An account about a greedy Egyptian priest who refused to visit a dying old woman, who venerated the Mother of God, and 
                           went to a dying money lender. </note>                                         
                     </msItem>
                     
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.52">
                        <locus from="52v" to="53r"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5022MiraclePeterSirloyos" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወሀሎ᎓ ፩ደብር᎓ ውስተ᎓ አሐቲ᎓ ሀገር᎓ ዘስማ᎓ ደብረ᎓ ምጥማቅ᎓   </incipit>                    
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"></explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 173.  CREATE AN ID!!!!!!. An account about a nun from the Egyptian monastery of Dabra Metmaq. She was saved by 
                           the Mother of God from a sin with a rich young man, who himself repented, dispersed his possessions and went into
                           a monastery. </note>                                         
                     </msItem> 
                     
                     <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.53">
                        <locus from="53v" to="54r"/>
                        <title type="complete" ref="LIT5022MiraclePeterSirloyos" xml:lang="gez"/>
                        <textLang mainLang="gez"/>
                        <incipit xml:lang="gez">ወሀሎ᎓ ውስተ᎓ ሀገረ᎓ ሮሜ᎓ አመ᎓ መዋዕለ᎓ ንጉሠ᎓ ሳባ᎓ ፈተውኩ᎓   </incipit>                    
                        <explicit xml:lang="gez"></explicit>                   
                        <note> Numbered 174.  CREATE AN ID!!!!!!. An account about the sheperd Paul who gave his soul to Devil and 
                           was saved in the cathedral of St. Paul, outside of the city. </note>                                                                 
                     </msItem> 
                     
                  </msItem>
